# Flask Usage Demonstration

This notebook demonstrates the usage of the Flask app's `/convert` and `/analyze` routes.
In[]:
## Convert Route

The `/convert` route converts an image from one format to another. In this example, we convert a PNG image to JPEG format.
In[7]:
import requests
from PIL import Image
from io import BytesIO

# URL of the Flask app's /convert route
url = "http://127.0.0.1:5000/convert"

# Path to the image you want to convert
image_path = "image.png"  # Update this to the actual path of the image

# Specify the desired output format
data = {'format': 'JPEG'}

# Open the image file in binary mode
with open(image_path, 'rb') as img_file:
    files = {'image': img_file}
    
    # Send the POST request to the /convert route
    response = requests.post(url, files=files, data=data)
    
    # Display the converted image
    if response.status_code == 200:
        img = Image.open(BytesIO(response.content))
        img.show()
    else:
        print("Failed to convert image:", response.text)
In[]:
## Analyze Route

The `/analyze` route analyzes a given text for sentiment (polarity and subjectivity). In this example, we analyze the sentence "I love coding in Python!".
In[8]:
# URL of the Flask app's /analyze route
url = "http://127.0.0.1:5000/analyze"

# Text to analyze
text = "I love coding in Python!"

# Send the GET request to the /analyze route
response = requests.get(url, params={'text': text})

# Display the analysis result
if response.status_code == 200:
    analysis = response.json()
    print("Polarity:", analysis['polarity'])
    print("Subjectivity:", analysis['subjectivity'])
else:
    print("Failed to analyze text:", response.text)

Polarity: 0.625
Subjectivity: 0.6
